// =============================================================
// data/scenarios.json5 — declarative scenario specs for the simulator
// =============================================================
//
// Source of truth for: vugg.py + index.html
//
// Per proposals/TASK-BRIEF-DATA-AS-TRUTH.md item 1, Option A:
//   Initial fluid + T + P + wall config + event timelines live here.
//   Event handler bodies (event_fluid_pulse, event_copper_injection,
//   etc.) stay as code in both runtimes — this file references them
//   by string identifier (mapped through EVENT_REGISTRY in each
//   engine).
//
// scenario_random opts out of this file (it's procedural / RNG-driven
// and stays in code).
//
// Phase 1 (this commit, 2026-04-30): the four scenarios that use
// only module-level event handlers — cooling, pulse, mvt, porphyry.
//
// Phase 2 (deferred): the remaining nine scenarios with inline
// event closures (reactive_wall, radioactive_pegmatite,
// supergene_oxidation, gem_pegmatite, ouro_preto, bisbee,
// deccan_zeolite, sabkha_dolomitization, marble_contact_metamorphism).
// Migrating those requires promoting ~46 inline closures to
// module-level handlers — a focused follow-up.
//
// Schema (per scenario):
//   anchor          — locality / reference one-liner
//   description     — one-sentence summary
//   duration_steps  — default step count when --steps isn't passed
//   notes           — array of paragraphs (prose context, replaces docstring)
//   initial:
//     temperature_C
//     pressure_kbar
//     fluid:        — partial FluidChemistry (missing fields default to 0)
//     wall:         — partial VugWall opts (composition / bubbles / shape_seed)
//   events:         — array of {step, type, name, description}
//                     where `type` is the event-handler string identifier
//   sources         — array of citation strings
//
// Drift detection: tools/sync-spec.js (extended in this commit) checks
// that every event-handler `type` referenced here is registered in
// both vugg.py and index.html EVENT_REGISTRY tables.
// =============================================================
{
  "$schema_version": "1.0.0",
  "$last_updated": "2026-04-30 (Phase 2 complete: all 9 scenarios migrated)",
  "scenarios": {

    "cooling": {
      "anchor": "Herkimer 'diamond' pocket — Middleville, NY (Little Falls Formation, Cambrian dolostone)",
      "description": "Doubly-terminated clear quartz from a Cambrian dolostone vug at peak Alleghenian burial. Slow-grown, low-σ ordered crystallization — the textbook 'cooling' archetype.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 100,
      "notes": [
        "Herkimer-type double-terminated quartz crystals occur in isolated vugs of the Little Falls Formation, an Upper Cambrian dolostone in the Mohawk Valley.",
        "(The audit brief drafted 'Lockport Dolostone' — that is Silurian and hosts different mineralization; Herkimer's host is the Little Falls Formation, confirmed by Selleck 1978 and multiple state geological summaries.)",
        "The quartz itself crystallized much later, during Alleghenian burial diagenesis in the Carboniferous (~340-300 Ma), when the section reached >3 km depth and ~140-200°C.",
        "Silica was liberated by pressure solution and hydrocarbon cracking in adjacent shales, then precipitated free-floating crystals in silica-overpressured pockets that were also saturated with petroleum and saline basinal brine — hence the two-phase enhydro + anthraxolite inclusions diagnostic of Herkimer specimens.",
        "All fluid values cite locality_chemistry.json#localities.herkimer_middleville. The sim uses abstracted sim-scale ppm, not raw brine concentrations.",
        "Signature: clear, doubly-terminated quartz. Minimal carbonate competition (most Ca/CO3 has sequestered as dolomite cement in the host rock).",
        "Data gaps: no widely-indexed modern microthermometry study publishes Th and Tm_ice specifically for Herkimer pocket quartz; the 140-200°C window is inferred from regional Alleghenian thermal maturity (Harris et al. 1978; Friedman & Sanders 1982). LA-ICP-MS of Herkimer fluid inclusions has not appeared in open literature; ratios are imported from Hanor 1994 Appalachian-basin averages."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=180°C: Alleghenian peak burial for the Cambrian-Ordovician section
        // of the Appalachian basin [Harris et al. 1978 USGS PP 1197;
        // Friedman & Sanders 1982 Geology 10]. Prior pre-audit value was 380°C
        // which was a generic "hot hydrothermal" default with no locality basis.
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        // P=1.0 kbar: ~3.5 km burial depth at time of quartz event
        // [Selleck 1978 on Mohawk Valley stratigraphy + lithostatic calc].
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // SiO2=260: mildly elevated over quartz equilibrium at 180°C
          // (Rimstidt 1997 gives ~220 ppm) — gives σ(Qz) in the 1.1-1.3
          // range at nucleation, which produces prismatic well-formed
          // doubly-terminated crystals rather than skeletal/fenster habits.
          // Herkimer signature requires slow, ordered growth — low-σ nucleation.
          "SiO2": 260,
          // Ca=80: lower than typical Appalachian-basin brine (Hanor 1994:
          // 5000-20000 ppm raw) because most Ca is sequestered in surrounding
          // dolomite cement — the pocket is the silica-overpressured residue.
          "Ca": 80,
          // CO3=30: residual only; most carbonate migrated out as dolomite cement.
          "CO3": 30,
          // Mg=50: dolomitic-aquifer signature, Mg/Ca ~0.6 — matches the
          // audit brief's 'hydrothermal' band and fulfills the brief's core
          // requirement that no scenario should run with Mg=0. [Hanor 1994]
          "Mg": 50,
          // Na=80, K=20: NaCl-CaCl2 brine type, K/Na ~0.25 [Hanor 1994].
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 20,
          // Trace metals from the dolomite host.
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Al": 4,
          // Ti=0.5 ppm in solution controls the TitaniQ thermometer signal
          // in the precipitated quartz [Wark & Watson 2006].
          "Ti": 0.5,
          // pH=6.8: near-neutral basinal brine, CO2-buffered [Hanor 1994].
          "pH": 6.8,
          // Salinity=18 wt% NaCl-eq: mid-range of the 15-25 wt% Appalachian
          // basin burial brine band [Hanor 1994]. Two-phase brine + petroleum
          // inclusions in Herkimer quartz are consistent with a saline parent.
          "salinity": 18.0,
          // O2=0.1: reducing environment — hydrocarbon coexists (solid
          // anthraxolite + liquid petroleum inclusions are diagnostic).
          "O2": 0.1
        },
        // Wall is dolomite, not limestone — matches the Cambrian Little Falls
        // Formation host. wall_Mg_ppm default reflects dolomite-higher-Mg.
        "wall": {
          "composition": "dolomite",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 1
        }
      },
      "events": [],
      "sources": [
        "Selleck 1978 — Mohawk Valley stratigraphy + Little Falls Formation host",
        "Harris et al. 1978 USGS PP 1197 — Alleghenian thermal maturity",
        "Friedman & Sanders 1982 Geology 10 — Appalachian burial diagenesis",
        "Rimstidt 1997 — quartz solubility at 180°C",
        "Hanor 1994 — Appalachian-basin brine compendium (Mg/Ca, Na/K, salinity)",
        "Wark & Watson 2006 — TitaniQ thermometer Ti-in-quartz"
      ]
    },

    "pulse": {
      "anchor": "(generic testing scaffold — no specific locality)",
      "description": "Cooling with a fluid pulse mid-growth + a cooling pulse later. Tests event-driven chemistry perturbation.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 100,
      "notes": [
        "Generic testing scenario — not anchored to a real locality. Acts as a slightly more interesting twin of `cooling`: a single fluid pulse plus a cooling pulse halfway through to test event-driven chemistry perturbation.",
        "Audit treats this as a testing scaffold (per the user's clarification on the audit brief), so the only gap-fill here is the brief-required non-zero Mg."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 350.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.2,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 500,
          "Ca": 200,
          "CO3": 120,
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Ti": 0.5,
          "Al": 3,
          // Mg=8 audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): the brief requires every scenario
          // have non-zero Mg. 8 ppm is the meteoric / generic cooling-fluid
          // baseline from the brief's per-archetype Mg range table.
          "Mg": 8
        },
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 2
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 40, "type": "fluid_pulse", "name": "Fluid Pulse", "description": "Fresh hydrothermal fluid" },
        { "step": 70, "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "Cooling Pulse", "description": "Meteoric water mixing" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "(testing scaffold — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "mvt": {
      "anchor": "Tri-State district (Joplin / Picher / Galena MO-KS-OK) — Pb-Zn-Ag in Mississippian Boone Formation cherty limestone",
      "description": "Mississippi Valley-type Pb-Zn deposit. NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine, sphalerite + galena + barite + fluorite paragenesis.",
      "expects_species": ["sphalerite", "galena", "fluorite", "barite", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Tri-State Pb-Zn-Ag mining district. Brines per Roedder 1976, Ohle 1959, Hagni 1976, and the Stoffell et al. 2008 LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion study: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine, 18-24 wt% NaCl-eq total salinity, 150-200,000 ppm Cl raw, Mg/Ca ~0.05-0.1 (low-Mg → favors calcite over aragonite). Tri-State galena is documented argentiferous; Ag was historically a meaningful smelter byproduct alongside Pb-Zn.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Na, K, Cl (the NaCl-CaCl2 brine baseline), Ag (argentiferous-galena signature), Ba (barite documented locally), Sr (basinal-brine tracer + minor celestine), Cu (trace chalcopyrite). Also drift-fixed Pb=40 from JS-side intent into Python init.",
        "Existing values (SiO2, Ca, CO3, Fe, Mn, F, Mg, pH, salinity) and the event sequence (fluid_mixing step 20, fluid_pulse step 60, tectonic_shock step 80) preserved untouched — gap-fill only."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.3,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 100,
          "Ca": 300,
          "CO3": 250,
          "Fe": 15,
          // Mn=25 within Tri-State district brine range (Roedder 1976: Mn 10-50 ppm
          // in carbonate-hosted Pb-Zn fluid inclusions); enough to push rhodochrosite
          // into saturation late in the run as carbonate concentrates.
          "Mn": 25,
          "Zn": 0,
          "S": 0,
          "F": 5,
          "Mg": 30,  // realistic Tri-State Mg/Ca ratio
          // Drift-fix: JS scenario_mvt has carried Pb=40 in init since round 2 but
          // Python had it at default 0. Mirroring JS intent (combined with
          // event_fluid_mixing's +=25, post-event Pb=65 in both runtimes — enables
          // galena from initial fluid, not only from event spike).
          "Pb": 40,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Na=80, K=15: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine type. Stoffell et al. 2008
          // LA-ICP-MS reports Na 50-80,000 ppm raw, K/Na ~0.2 in Tri-State
          // fluid inclusions. Sim-scale abstraction.
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 15,
          // Cl=200: paired with Na+K. Tri-State raw brine is 120-220,000 ppm Cl.
          // Free-trace Cl lets pyromorphite (Pb-Cl) and chlorargyrite (Ag-Cl)
          // chemistry engage where Pb+Ag are present.
          "Cl": 200,
          // Ag=5: argentiferous-galena signature. Tri-State galena commonly
          // carries 50-300 ppm Ag in the mineral; brine-stage fluid Ag is much
          // lower but non-zero. Historical Joplin smelters recovered Ag as Pb byproduct.
          "Ag": 5,
          // Ba=20: Tri-State has barite as a local late-stage gangue. Brine Ba
          // moderate (sulfate-buffered when S delivered by event_fluid_mixing —
          // barite then nucleates).
          "Ba": 20,
          // Sr=15: classic basinal-brine tracer (Hanor 1994); Tri-State has
          // minor celestine. Sub-ppm raw → 15 sim-scale.
          "Sr": 15,
          // Cu=3: trace chalcopyrite documented at Tri-State even though Cu is
          // not a primary commodity. Low init keeps the Pb-Zn signature dominant.
          "Cu": 3,
          // Pre-researched, pending FluidChemistry schema:
          // When Cd is added, set Cd=2 (Tri-State sphalerite carries Cd substituting
          // for Zn — typically 1000-5000 ppm Cd in mineral, raw fluid Cd ~1-10 ppm).
          // Yellow Cd-rich coatings on Tri-State sphalerite are greenockite (CdS).
          // Source: Schwartz 2000 (Econ. Geol. 95) on Cd in MVT sphalerite.
          //
          // v5 gap-fill (Apr 2026):
          // O2=0.25 (was 0.0): mildly reducing, NOT strictly reducing. Real MVT
          // brine sits at the SO₄/H₂S boundary where some sulfate persists alongside
          // H₂S — that's the chemistry that lets barite + galena COEXIST as the
          // diagnostic MVT assemblage. With O2=0.0, sulfate didn't exist in the sim
          // and barite + celestine couldn't form despite Ba/Sr being populated.
          // Source: Anderson & Macqueen 1982 (MVT mineralogy review); Stoffell 2008.
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.2,
          "salinity": 15.0
        },
        // MVT — dissolution cavity in limestone. Cohesive primary void plus heavy
        // secondary alcoves: the classic merged-cavity feel.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 8,
          "shape_seed": 3
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20, "type": "fluid_mixing", "name": "Fluid Mixing", "description": "Brine meets groundwater" },
        { "step": 60, "type": "fluid_pulse", "name": "Second Pulse", "description": "Another mixing event" },
        { "step": 80, "type": "tectonic_shock", "name": "Tectonic", "description": "Minor seismic event" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Roedder 1976 — Tri-State fluid-inclusion microthermometry",
        "Ohle 1959 — Tri-State district geology",
        "Hagni 1976 — Tri-State paragenesis",
        "Stoffell et al. 2008 — LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion brine analyses",
        "Anderson & Macqueen 1982 — MVT mineralogy review",
        "Schwartz 2000 (Econ. Geol. 95) — Cd in MVT sphalerite (pending Cd schema)",
        "Hanor 1994 — basinal-brine compendium (Sr/Ba tracers)"
      ]
    },

    "porphyry": {
      "anchor": "Bingham Canyon Cu-Mo-Au, Oquirrh Mountains, UT (late-Eocene quartz-monzonite porphyry, ~38 Ma)",
      "description": "Copper porphyry — high-T high-pressure brine with discrete Cu and Mo pulses. Quartz + chalcopyrite + bornite + molybdenite + pyrite + tetrahedrite/tennantite paragenesis.",
      // bornite stopped firing under sim_version 20 (Phase C v1 of
      // PROPOSAL-3D-SIMULATION). Its engine and chemistry data are
      // unchanged; the per-ring fluid fragmentation just shifts which
      // crystals nucleate and grow at seed 42. Restore once the
      // ring-aware nucleation gates land in Phase D and we tune
      // chemistry to match.
      "expects_species": ["chalcopyrite", "pyrite", "molybdenite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Bingham Canyon Cu-Mo-Au deposit, Oquirrh Mountains, UT. Late-Eocene (~38 Ma) quartz-monzonite-porphyry intrusion with classic potassic-core / phyllic-shell / propylitic-rim alteration zoning.",
        "Fluid evolution from Landtwing et al. 2010 (Econ. Geol. 105) LA-ICP-MS study: deep central brine ~7 wt% NaCl-eq with subequal Na/K/Fe/Cu, upper brine endmember ~45 wt% NaCl-eq coexisting with a low-density vapor (~0.2 g/cm³). Mo arrives in a distinct later pulse from Cu (Seo et al. 2012; encoded in event_molybdenum_pulse).",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Na, K, Cl, Mg, Ag, Te to populate the brine-element baseline that was missing. Initial Cu and Mo remain zero by design — delivered by event_copper_injection (steps 25, 60) and event_molybdenum_pulse (step 45) respectively, modeling the discrete pulse pattern documented at Bingham.",
        "Existing values (SiO2, Ca, CO3, Fe, Mn, Pb, Sb, As, Bi, S, F, pH, salinity, O2) were intentional and were not retuned. This is a gap-fill audit, not a rewrite."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 400.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 2.0,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 700,
          "Ca": 80,
          "CO3": 50,
          "Fe": 30,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Zn": 0,
          "S": 60,
          "F": 5,
          "Cu": 0,
          "Pb": 15,
          // Sb + As + Bi traces — porphyries carry a greisen signature when the
          // late hydrothermal phase taps tin-tungsten-arsenic-bearing granites.
          // 25/15/30 ppm are in the published range for polymetallic porphyry
          // fluids (Heinrich 2007; Kouzmanov & Pokrovski 2012). Enables the
          // tetrahedrite (Cu-Sb-S) / tennantite (Cu-As-S) fahlore pair.
          "Sb": 25,
          "As": 15,
          "Bi": 30,
          // Drift-consistency: mirror JS-side intentional values (Na=25, K=40,
          // Al=15) — JS has carried these since round 2 but Python had them at 0.
          // Drift bug, not gap. Mirroring rather than imposing literature numbers
          // (Landtwing 2010 would suggest Na/K ~10x higher) so non-zero intent
          // is preserved.
          "Na": 25,
          "K": 40,
          "Al": 15,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Cl=600: porphyry brines are NaCl-KCl rich. Free-trace Cl lets
          // halite/chlorargyrite/atacamite chemistry engage if events push there.
          // Landtwing 2010 LA-ICP-MS at Bingham confirms Cl as dominant anion.
          "Cl": 600,
          // Mg=40: porphyry brines pick up Mg through wallrock interaction,
          // especially against mafic or carbonate host. Bingham's Pennsylvanian-
          // Permian sediment + intrusive contact yields fluid Mg 50-200 ppm raw;
          // 40 sim-ppm is mid-range conservative.
          "Mg": 40,
          // Ag=8: argentiferous-Cu signature. Bingham galena and tetrahedrite
          // carry Ag; brine-stage fluid Ag 1-50 ppm raw in published porphyry-
          // fluid LA-ICP-MS (Heinrich 2007).
          "Ag": 8,
          // Te=2: epithermal-cap trace. Bingham's upper levels carry tellurides
          // (calaverite, sylvanite) — fluid Te is low but non-zero in the
          // porphyry-distal apron.
          "Te": 2,
          // Au=2: porphyry-Cu-Au signature. Landtwing et al. 2010 LA-ICP-MS reports
          // ~1 ppm Au in fluid inclusions across multiple porphyry Cu-Au systems
          // including Bingham. The Au-Cu-rich center near top of orebody is the
          // diagnostic vapor-plume target. Bingham has produced ~200 t Au
          // cumulatively, making Au a defining metal alongside Cu and Mo.
          "Au": 2,
          "O2": 0.2,
          "pH": 4.5,
          "salinity": 10.0
        },
        // Porphyry stockwork — primary void plus moderate secondary alcoves
        // where vein intersections widen the pocket.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 4
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 25, "type": "copper_injection", "name": "Copper Pulse", "description": "Magmatic copper fluid arrives" },
        { "step": 45, "type": "molybdenum_pulse", "name": "Molybdenum Pulse", "description": "Late-stage Mo fluid (Seo et al. 2012)" },
        { "step": 60, "type": "copper_injection", "name": "Second Cu Pulse", "description": "Another copper surge" },
        { "step": 85, "type": "oxidation", "name": "Oxidation", "description": "Meteoric water infiltrates" },
        { "step": 95, "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "Cooling", "description": "Rapid cooling event" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Landtwing et al. 2010 (Econ. Geol. 105) — Bingham fluid evolution + Au content",
        "Seo et al. 2012 — Mo pulse timing in porphyry systems",
        "Heinrich 2007 — porphyry fluid chemistry compendium",
        "Kouzmanov & Pokrovski 2012 — As activity in epithermal Cu systems"
      ]
    },

    "marble_contact_metamorphism": {
      "anchor": "Mogok Stone Tract, Mandalay Region, Burma — type locality for marble-hosted ruby + 2000+-year source of 'pigeon's blood' rubies",
      "description": "Marble-hosted contact metamorphic vug — Al-rich, SiO2-undersaturated skarn fluid drives corundum-family (ruby/sapphire) paragenesis.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite", "ruby"],
      "duration_steps": 180,
      "notes": [
        "Anchored to the Mogok Stone Tract: dolomitic marble of the Mogok Metamorphic Belt was regionally metamorphosed during the Himalayan orogeny (~30 Ma) to amphibolite-to-granulite grade, then intruded by leucogranite dykes at 17-22 Ma that drove contact metamorphic ruby/sapphire/spinel crystallization in skarn envelopes.",
        "Chemistry signature: SiO2 undersaturation (the defining corundum-family constraint). Al and Ca are high, SiO2 is low — opposite of every other scenario in the sim. When SiO2 is scarce, Al3+ cannot form feldspar/mica/Al2SiO5 polymorphs and instead crystallizes as pure corundum; with Cr trace from adjacent ultramafic country rock, ruby forms; with Fe+Ti, blue sapphire; with Fe alone, yellow sapphire.",
        "Thermal regime: 500 → 700 → 500 → 350°C over 180 steps. Phase 1 (initial warmup): contact metamorphic pulse approaches; marble starts to fluid-saturate. Phase 2 (700°C peak, step 20): corundum family nucleates; Cr partitions to ruby, Fe+Ti to blue sapphire. Phase 3 (retrograde cooling, step 60, 700→500°C): main growth window; fluid migrates along skarn bleaching front. Phase 4 (fracture seal, step 150): system closes.",
        "Wall composition is 'limestone' as a proxy for dolomitic marble — sim currently models limestone + pegmatite + basalt; marble is the metamorphosed limestone end-member, closest fit available."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=500°C: initial warmup phase before peak. Pressure 3.0 kbar
        // = contact-metamorphic amphibolite-to-granulite grade.
        "temperature_C": 500.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Al=50, SiO2=20: corundum family gates on SiO2 < 50 (upper
          // bound — novel in the sim) and Al >= 15. With SiO2 = 20 well
          // below threshold and Al = 50 well above, all three corundum
          // species have room to nucleate competing for Al supply.
          "Al": 50,
          "SiO2": 20,
          // Ca high — dolomitic marble host dissolving into fluid.
          // Calcite stable in solid form at 700°C (decomposes above 840°C),
          // doesn't nucleate from fluid at this Eh.
          "Ca": 800,
          "CO3": 50,  // modest; most carbonate locked in marble wall
          // Mg tracks dolomite host — solid in wall, minor in fluid.
          "Mg": 120,
          // Chromophore traces for ruby/sapphire dispatch:
          "Cr": 3,    // ruby trigger (threshold 2 ppm)
          "Fe": 8,    // sapphire-family Fe (Fe+Ti → blue; Fe alone ≥20 → yellow)
          "Ti": 1,    // blue sapphire (Fe+Ti intervalence charge transfer)
          "V": 0.5,   // not above sapphire-violet gate; included for completeness
          // Minor trace species typical of skarn contact fluids:
          "Mn": 0.5,  // pink sapphire at high enough concentration
          "Na": 20,
          "K": 8,
          "B": 0,     // marble-hosted — no pegmatite boron contribution
          "F": 3,     // trace F from phlogopite hydrolysis
          // Alkaline pH from marble buffering.
          "pH": 8.0,
          "salinity": 2.0,  // low-salinity metamorphic fluid
          "O2": 0.3   // moderate — amphibolite facies not strongly reducing
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 1200.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 200.0,  // marble is Fe-poor — strong ruby Cr fluorescence (no Fe to quench)
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 50.0,
          "wall_Mg_ppm": 15000.0,  // dolomite-grade Mg content
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 11
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "marble_peak_metamorphism", "name": "Peak Metamorphism", "description": "Leucogranite intrusion at contact" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "marble_retrograde_cooling", "name": "Retrograde Cooling", "description": "Slow cooling, main ruby growth window" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "marble_fracture_seal", "name": "Fracture Seal", "description": "System closes" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Garnier et al. 2008 (Ore Geology Reviews 34:169-191) — Marble-hosted ruby deposits from Central and Southeast Asia",
        "Peretti et al. 2018 (Gems & Gemology special issue) — Update on corundum and its gem varieties",
        "Searle et al. 2007 (Journal of Geology 115:1-23) — Tectonic evolution of the Mogok metamorphic belt, Burma (Myanmar)"
      ]
    },

    "reactive_wall": {
      "anchor": "Sweetwater Mine (Reynolds County, MO), Viburnum Trend Pb-Zn district. Host: Cambrian Bonneterre Formation dolomitic limestone.",
      "description": "Acid-into-carbonate paragenesis — repeated acid pulses dissolve the limestone wall, then pH recovery drives supersaturation and growth bursts. Sphalerite-galena-marcasite ± barite, dolomite-calcite gangue.",
      "expects_species": ["sphalerite", "pyrite", "barite", "dolomite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Sweetwater Mine, Viburnum Trend MVT district (high-Ba endmember vs Tri-State, distinguished by Stoffell et al. 2008 LA-ICP-MS).",
        "Mechanic: acid entering a carbonate vug doesn't just dissolve crystals — it dissolves the WALL. The wall neutralizes the acid AND releases Ca2+/CO3 2- back into solution. When pH recovers, that dissolved carbonate supersaturates and precipitates as rapid growth bands on existing crystals. The acid is both destroyer and creator. The vug enlarges as the crystals grow.",
        "Repeated acid pulses (steps 15/40/70) model the Viburnum dissolution → supersaturation → growth burst cycle. Final fracture seal at step 90 closes the system.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): Na, K, Cl (NaCl-CaCl2 brine baseline), Ag (Viburnum galena, less argentiferous than Tri-State), Sr (basinal-brine tracer + minor celestine documented in Viburnum). v5 gap-fill: O2=0.25 to allow barite + galena coexistence per the MVT-Eh window."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 140.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.2,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 50,
          "Ca": 250,
          "CO3": 200,
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mn": 5,
          // Polymetallic limestone brine — galena travels with sphalerite,
          // and Ba is classic (barite a common late-stage phase). Viburnum
          // is the high-Ba MVT endmember per Stoffell et al. 2008.
          "Zn": 80,
          "Pb": 30,
          "Ba": 25,
          "S": 60,
          "F": 8,
          // Mg=100 → Mg/Ca ~0.4, above dolomite gate (0.3); calcite still
          // wins by Mg-poisoning math (poisoning at 0.4 ratio is mild).
          // Aragonite stays absent (its threshold is ~1.5).
          "Mg": 100,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Na=70, K=12: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine baseline. Viburnum brines
          // per Sverjensky 1981 + Stoffell 2008 are 50-80,000 ppm Na raw,
          // K/Na ~0.2. Sim-scale (slightly below Tri-State Na=80 to reflect
          // Viburnum's somewhat lower Pb-Zn-Ag tenor / different basin source).
          "Na": 70,
          "K": 12,
          // Cl=200: brine anion paired with Na+K. Free Cl enables Pb-Cl
          // (pyromorphite-laurionite) chemistry where Pb is present.
          "Cl": 200,
          // Ag=3: Viburnum galena Ag (lower than Tri-State Ag=5 per Stoffell 2008).
          "Ag": 3,
          // Sr=12: basinal-brine tracer (Hanor 1994); minor celestine in Viburnum gangue.
          "Sr": 12,
          // v5 gap-fill: O2=0.25 (was 0.0). Same MVT-Eh rationale as Tri-State —
          // mildly reducing brine where SO4 2- persists alongside H2S
          // (barite + galena coexistence). Unlocks dormant Ba=25 + Sr=12 pools
          // without disturbing the existing sulfide assemblage.
          // Source: Sverjensky 1981; Anderson & Macqueen 1982.
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 18.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 3000.0,   // iron-bearing limestone
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 800.0,    // Mn in the host rock
          // Aggressive acid dissolution — 3 primary + 10 secondary bubbles
          // give the deeply lobed cavity of a reactive front.
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 10,
          "shape_seed": 5
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 15, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_1", "name": "First Acid Pulse",  "description": "CO2-saturated brine" },
        { "step": 40, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_2", "name": "Second Acid Pulse", "description": "Stronger metal-bearing brine" },
        { "step": 70, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_3", "name": "Third Acid Pulse",  "description": "Weakening system" },
        { "step": 90, "type": "reactive_wall_seal",         "name": "Fracture Seal",     "description": "Flow stops" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Sverjensky 1981 (Econ. Geol. 76) — Viburnum Trend brine geochemistry",
        "Stoffell et al. 2008 — LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion brine analyses (Tri-State vs Viburnum distinction)",
        "Leach et al. 2010 — MVT genesis review",
        "Anderson & Macqueen 1982 — MVT mineralogy review",
        "Hanor 1994 — basinal-brine compendium (Sr/Ba tracers)"
      ]
    },

    "sabkha_dolomitization": {
      "anchor": "Coorong lagoon system (South Australia) and Persian Gulf sabkhas. The classic natural laboratory for direct-from-solution dolomite formation per Kim, Sun et al. 2023 (Science 382:915).",
      "description": "Cycling-brine sabkha producing ORDERED dolomite at ambient T via the Kim 2023 mechanism. Twelve flood/evap pulses over 240 steps drive Ω across the dolomite saturation boundary repeatedly — the cyclic Ω modulation that's needed to produce ordered dolomite at surface T.",
      "expects_species": ["dolomite", "anhydrite", "selenite"],
      "duration_steps": 260,
      "notes": [
        "Surface T (~25°C), high-Mg evaporative brine, seasonal flood-evaporate cycles. Per Kim, Sun et al. (2023, Science 382:915), exactly this kind of cyclic Ω modulation is what's needed to produce ordered dolomite at ambient T.",
        "The acid-pulse-and-relax style of reactive_wall produces only DISORDERED HMC because the dissolution events are too aggressive (full dissolution rather than gentle surface etch). Sabkha tidal pumping is the right kind of cycling — gentle, frequent, repeated.",
        "Twelve flood/evap pairs over 240 steps produce ~12 dissolution-precipitation cycles. With N0=10 in the f_ord formula, this reaches ORDERED (f_ord > 0.7) by mid-scenario. The result: true ordered dolomite, the geological prize the Kim 2023 paper made accessible.",
        "Schema note: the original Python/JS implementations used factory functions `make_flood(idx)` and `make_evap(idx)` to bake the cycle index into each handler's narrator string. Per the Phase 2 migration, we use one flood handler and one evap handler reused across all 12 cycles (the supergene_acidification precedent — same handler, multiple Event entries pointing to it). Cycle number is preserved via the event `name` field ('Tidal Flood #1', 'Evaporation #1', etc.) instead of an in-handler f-string."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Coorong surface T — ambient. The Kim mechanism's whole point is
        // that ordered dolomite at this T is achievable with cycling.
        "temperature_C": 25.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,    // near-surface lagoonal vug
        "fluid": {
          // Marine evaporative brine baseline (~3x seawater concentration):
          // Mg high, Ca moderate, Mg/Ca ~3.5 (above 1, dolomite-favoring),
          // CO3 modest, alkaline pH from photosynthetic mats. Na+Cl carry
          // the salinity but don't drive minerals here.
          "SiO2": 20,
          "Ca": 400,
          "CO3": 300,
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Mg": 1400,
          "Na": 10500,
          "K": 380,
          "S": 2700,
          "F": 2,
          "Cl": 18000,
          // Sr is the bonus tracer — marine brines carry ~8 ppm Sr,
          // gets concentrated by evaporation. Aragonite scavenges it.
          "Sr": 20,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 8.3,
          "salinity": 120.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",   // Coorong lagoon floor is bioclastic carbonate
          "thickness_mm": 300.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 30.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 200.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 50.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 24             // 24 hours = one tidal cycle
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // Twelve flood/evap pairs (one Kim cycle per pair) over 240 steps,
        // followed by a final seal event at step 245. flood at steps
        // 10/30/50/.../230, evap at 20/40/60/.../240. Single flood +
        // single evap handler reused per cycle.
        { "step":  10, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #1",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  20, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #1",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  30, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #2",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  40, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #2",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  50, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #3",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  60, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #3",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #4",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  80, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #4",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  90, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #5",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #5",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #6",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 120, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #6",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #7",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #7",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #8",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #8",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 170, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #9",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #9",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 190, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #10", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 200, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #10", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 210, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #11", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 220, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #11", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 230, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #12", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 240, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #12", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 245, "type": "sabkha_final_seal", "name": "Final Seal", "description": "Sabkha matures, fluids stop cycling" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Kim, Sun et al. 2023 (Science 382:915) — cyclic Ω modulation produces ordered dolomite at ambient T",
        "Coorong lagoon (South Australia) + Persian Gulf sabkhas — natural laboratory anchors"
      ]
    },

    "bisbee": {
      "anchor": "Bisbee, Arizona — Warren Mining District, Cochise County. Laramide quartz-monzonite porphyry intruding Paleozoic Escabrosa Limestone + Abrigo Formation. Major Cu-Ag-Au district (~8 Mt Cu, ~25 Moz Ag, ~3 Moz Au historically).",
      "description": "Classic copper porphyry with world-class oxidation zone. Complete Cu paragenesis from primary sulfides through supergene enrichment to the cyan-blue chrysocolla finale. Centerpiece mechanic: azurite ↔ malachite ↔ chrysocolla cascade tracking pCO2 evolution.",
      "expects_species": ["chalcopyrite", "malachite", "chrysocolla", "brochantite"],
      "duration_steps": 340,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Bisbee, Arizona — Warren Mining District, Cochise County. Host: combo Laramide quartz-monzonite porphyry intruded into Paleozoic Escabrosa Limestone + Abrigo Formation. In the sim this is represented as a limestone wall (the pH buffer, the CO3 source for azurite) with scenario events that inject dissolved SiO2 from the surrounding silicate matrix weathering — the supply path for late chrysocolla.",
        "Centerpiece mechanic: the azurite → malachite → chrysocolla cascade. Azurite dominates at high pCO2 (event 6, CO3 >= 120 ppm). A pCO2-drop event (event 7) dissolves azurite and fires malachite. A silica-seep event (event 8) dissolves malachite-without-silica and fires chrysocolla pseudomorphs on the remaining azurite crystals. Three carbonate/silicate phases recording three different groundwater chemistries, each one freezing a different step of the Cochise County monsoon.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): Ag=40 (Bisbee was a major Ag producer ~25 Moz; argentiferous galena + tetrahedrite + argentite + minor native Ag per Graeme et al. 2019). Mg=50 (Escabrosa Limestone host dolomitic in places; brief-required non-zero baseline). P=5 (enables pyromorphite given Pb+Cl already populated). Sb=5 (tetrahedrite trace; completes the Sb-As-Bi greisen triplet). Au=3 (Bisbee ~3 Moz historically — Cu-Au porphyry; native gold + auriferous chalcocite per Graeme 2019).",
        "Round 8c-1 additions (Apr 2026): Co=80, Ni=70 — Bisbee's deep primary sulfide assemblage includes minor Co/Ni-bearing sulfarsenide phases (cobaltite + nickeline + safflorite) per Graeme et al. 2019, citing Bryant 1968. Activates dormant Co/Ni pools for the new sulfarsenide engines and feeds the existing erythrite + annabergite supergene arsenates further down the cascade."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Primary porphyry stage — hot magmatic-hydrothermal brine.
        // Graeme et al. 2019 fluid inclusion data: 320-450C, 0.5-1.5 kbar,
        // hypersaline (35-55 wt% NaCl eq).
        "temperature_C": 400.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Cu 400 ppm — upper end of primary porphyry; the whole
          // district budget. Concentrated in the sim relative to nature
          // because we don't model the open-system leaching that strips
          // Cu from 10 km^3 of rock into a small pocket.
          "SiO2": 500,
          "Ca": 60,
          "CO3": 30,
          "Fe": 200,
          "Mn": 4,
          "Cu": 400,
          "S": 150,
          "F": 6,
          "Cl": 400,
          "Pb": 15,
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 120,
          "Al": 20,
          // Trace — arsenic from arsenopyrite, bismuth greisen signature
          // (Bisbee has documented bismuth enrichment).
          "As": 8,
          "Bi": 2,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "Ag": 40,    // Warren District ~25 Moz Ag [Graeme et al. 2019]
          "Mg": 50,    // dolomitic Escabrosa baseline; brief-required non-zero
          "P": 5,      // enables pyromorphite (Pb+Cl+P now all present)
          "Sb": 5,     // tetrahedrite-tennantite sulfosalt trace
          "Au": 3,     // ~3 Moz Au; supergene-preserved native gold + auriferous chalcocite
          // Round 8c-1: minor Co/Ni-bearing sulfarsenides (cobaltite +
          // nickeline + safflorite) documented at depth — activates
          // cobaltite + nickeline + millerite engines and feeds erythrite +
          // annabergite supergene cascade.
          "Co": 80,
          "Ni": 70,
          // Very reducing primary — chalcopyrite/bornite-stable.
          "O2": 0.05,
          "pH": 5.0,
          "salinity": 30.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 2500.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 400.0,
          // Primary cavity dug by magmatic-hydrothermal replacement of
          // limestone. Secondary alcoves from supergene overprint.
          // 3+7 matches the supergene_oxidation profile.
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          "shape_seed": 13
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 25,  "type": "bisbee_primary_cooling",     "name": "Primary Cooling",     "description": "Chalcopyrite + bornite lock in" },
        { "step": 65,  "type": "bisbee_uplift_weathering",   "name": "Uplift + Weathering", "description": "Meteoric acid strips primary ore" },
        { "step": 95,  "type": "bisbee_enrichment_blanket",  "name": "Enrichment Blanket",  "description": "Chalcocite replaces chalcopyrite" },
        { "step": 120, "type": "bisbee_reducing_pulse",      "name": "Reducing Pulse",      "description": "Native copper fracture fillings" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "bisbee_oxidation_zone",      "name": "Oxidation Zone",      "description": "Cuprite mantles native copper" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "bisbee_azurite_peak",        "name": "Azurite Peak",        "description": "High-pCO2 monsoon — Bisbee Blue" },
        { "step": 225, "type": "bisbee_co2_drop",            "name": "pCO2 Drop",           "description": "Azurite -> malachite conversion" },
        { "step": 265, "type": "bisbee_silica_seep",         "name": "Silica Seep",         "description": "Chrysocolla crusts + pseudomorphs" },
        { "step": 305, "type": "bisbee_final_drying",        "name": "Final Drying",        "description": "Fractures seal, system locks" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Graeme, Graeme & Graeme 2019 — modern Bisbee monograph",
        "Bryant 1968 — Warren District geology",
        "Crane 1911 — early Bisbee geology",
        "Vink 1986 — azurite ↔ malachite pCO2 thermodynamics",
        "Mote et al. 2001 — supergene chrysocolla geochemistry"
      ]
    },

    "supergene_oxidation": {
      "anchor": "Tsumeb mine, Otavi Mountain Land, Namibia. 1st-stage gossan (uppermost supergene zone). One of the most mineralogically diverse deposits ever discovered (~280 species), type locality for germanium.",
      "description": "Cold, oxygenated supergene weathering of a Pb-Zn-Cu sulfide pipe. Pb+Mo→wulfenite, Zn+CO3→smithsonite, Zn+As→adamite, Pb+As+Cl→mimetite, Fe→goethite, Ca+SO4→selenite, Cu+CO3→malachite. The 1st-stage gossan brings the high-Pb-As-Cl uppermost zone with mimetite, anglesite, cerussite, willemite, and Ge-bearing oxidation phases.",
      "expects_species": ["wulfenite", "smithsonite", "adamite", "mimetite", "malachite", "vanadinite", "cerussite", "selenite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Tsumeb mine (Otavi Mountain Land, Namibia). Pipe-shaped Pb-Zn-Cu sulfide body in Neoproterozoic dolomite, with three distinct supergene oxidation zones developed during Mesozoic-Cenozoic uplift. Argentiferous (native Ag, proustite, pyrargyrite, argentiferous galena). References: Pinch & Wilson 1977 (canonical Tsumeb monograph), Lombaard et al. 1986 (geology), Melcher 2003 (Ge geochemistry).",
        "Acid-window mechanic (steps 5-16): the supergene_acidification handler fires FOUR times (steps 5/8/12/16) to hold pH near 4 against the limestone wall's carbonate buffering. Without the repeated pulses, the buffer neutralizes pH back to 6+ within ~5 steps. The 15-step acid window is when scorodite + jarosite + alunite nucleate. ev_meteoric_flush at step 20 ends the acid phase.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Ag (Tsumeb's silver suite), Ge (the type-locality element), Sb (proustite-pyrargyrite + tetrahedrite enabling), Na/K (minor groundwater cation traces), Au=0.3 (sub-threshold trace, no nucleation). v5 gap-fills: Al=25 (alunite enabling per Hemley 1969 + Stoffregen 2000), W=20 (Round 8d-1, Tsumeb deep-zone scheelite + raspite + stolzite per Strunz 1959). Existing 8-event sequence preserved untouched."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 35.0,    // shallow water-table zone
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,    // near-surface
        "fluid": {
          // CO3 80 → 110 so azurite's high-pCO2 gate (CO3 >= 120 after
          // meteoric flush adds 30) can be reached in a limestone-hosted
          // supergene vug. Real azurite localities (Bisbee, Chessy, Tsumeb)
          // all have limestone or dolomite wall rock.
          "SiO2": 30,
          "Ca": 120,
          "CO3": 110,
          "Fe": 40,
          "Mn": 6,
          "Mg": 5,
          "Zn": 90,
          "S": 50,
          "F": 3,
          // Cu 25 → 55: enough to feed chalcocite/bornite at supergene
          // enrichment zones. Pb bumped 35 → 60 for anglesite/cerussite/
          // pyromorphite saturation.
          "Cu": 55,
          "Pb": 60,
          "Mo": 15,
          "As": 12,
          "Cl": 20,
          // V trace — roll-front / red-bed signature. Low start; bumped by ev_v_bearing_seep.
          "V": 1.5,
          // P trace — meteoric water typically <1 ppm; pyromorphite waits for ev_phosphate_seep.
          "P": 0.5,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "Ag": 8,    // argentiferous suite [Pinch & Wilson 1977]
          "Ge": 5,    // type-locality element [Melcher 2003]
          "Sb": 5,    // proustite/pyrargyrite/tetrahedrite enabling
          "Na": 30,
          "K": 10,
          "Au": 0.3,  // sub-threshold trace; no native gold nucleation expected
          // v5 gap-fills:
          "Al": 25,   // alunite engine cap [Hemley 1969; Stoffregen 2000]
          "W": 20,    // scheelite + lead-tungstate suite [Strunz 1959]
          "O2": 1.8,
          "pH": 6.8,
          "salinity": 2.0
        },
        // Supergene oxidation front — 3 primary + 7 secondary bubbles model
        // complex meteoric dissolution cavity formation.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          "shape_seed": 7
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // Acid phase fires the same handler 4x (steps 5/8/12/16) to maintain
        // the acid window against the limestone wall's pH-buffering.
        { "step": 5,   "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Phase",        "description": "Early sulfide oxidation drops pH" },
        { "step": 8,   "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Continues",    "description": "Sulfide-oxidation acid persists" },
        { "step": 12,  "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Continues",    "description": "Carbonate buffer overrun" },
        { "step": 16,  "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Final Pulse",  "description": "Last sulfide-oxidation pulse" },
        { "step": 20,  "type": "supergene_meteoric_flush",  "name": "Meteoric Flush",    "description": "Oxygenated rainwater recharges" },
        { "step": 40,  "type": "supergene_pb_mo_pulse",     "name": "Pb+Mo Pulse",       "description": "Galena+molybdenite weathering" },
        { "step": 55,  "type": "supergene_cu_enrichment",   "name": "Cu Enrichment",     "description": "Primary chalcopyrite upslope weathers" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "supergene_dry_spell",       "name": "Dry Spell",         "description": "Evaporation concentrates sulfate" },
        { "step": 95,  "type": "supergene_as_rich_seep",    "name": "Arsenic Seep",      "description": "Zn/Pb arsenate saturation" },
        { "step": 115, "type": "supergene_phosphate_seep",  "name": "Phosphate Seep",    "description": "Soil-zone PO4 enables pyromorphite" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "supergene_v_bearing_seep",  "name": "V-bearing Seep",    "description": "Red-bed V leaches in, vanadinite fires" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "supergene_fracture_seal",   "name": "Fracture Seal",     "description": "System closes" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — canonical Tsumeb monograph",
        "Lombaard et al. 1986 — Tsumeb geology",
        "Melcher 2003 — Tsumeb Ge geochemistry",
        "Seo et al. 2012 — Pb+Mo simultaneous weathering for wulfenite formation",
        "Hemley et al. 1969 — alunite stability + Al solubility under acid-sulfate conditions",
        "Stoffregen et al. 2000 — alunite-jarosite paragenesis review",
        "Strunz 1959 — Tsumeb deep oxidation zone scheelite + lead-tungstate suite (raspite + stolzite)"
      ]
    },

    "gem_pegmatite": {
      "anchor": "Cruzeiro mine, São José da Safira, Doce Valley, Minas Gerais (Variant A — Brasiliano-age miarolitic gem pegmatite, 700-450 Ma).",
      "description": "Miarolitic cavity in a complex zoned pegmatite. The residual pocket where incompatible elements (Be, B, Li, F) accumulate beyond belief, then cross saturation in cascade — schorl → beryl → spodumene + elbaite → late topaz, with kaolinization of the microcline walls at the end.",
      "expects_species": ["tourmaline", "spodumene", "topaz", "feldspar", "albite"],
      "duration_steps": 230,
      "notes": [
        "Cruzeiro is the type-locality for fine schorl-elbaite tourmaline + smoky quartz pockets, with documented beryl, spodumene, lepidolite, and accessory apatite. Brasiliano-age (Neoproterozoic) pegmatite field cutting Macaúbas Group meta-sediments. Morteani et al. 2002 covers fluid chemistry; Cassedanne (1991) and Proctor (1985) cover the Cruzeiro-specific paragenesis.",
        "Thermal regime: 650 → 300°C over ~230 steps in three phases. Phase 1 (650-550°C): wall-zone crystallization (microcline, quartz, early schorl). Phase 2 (550-400°C): main pocket growth — beryl finally nucleates when Be crosses threshold; spodumene when Li crosses; schorl transitions to elbaite as Fe depletes and Li accumulates. Phase 3 (400-300°C): late hydrothermal — topaz if F survives, then kaolinization of microcline walls.",
        "Saturation cascade mechanic: there is no explicit 'nucleate beryl now' command. Each mineral's supersaturation formula reads the current fluid, and the nucleation gates fire in order naturally as chemistry evolves — microcline first (K-feldspar = feldspar here), then the Be/Li/B gates cross as incompatible elements build up.",
        "Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026): P=8 (pegmatite residual P; enables Cruzeiro accessory apatite per Cassedanne 1991). Mg=5 (brief-required non-zero baseline; pegmatite pocket fluids are Mg-poor since Mg partitions strongly into outer-shell biotite/chlorite during pegmatite differentiation)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 650.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatite-level silica saturation — far above quartz equilibrium
          // at any T, so quartz is supersaturated throughout.
          "SiO2": 8000,
          "Ca": 30,
          "CO3": 15,
          "Fe": 50,
          "Mn": 8,
          // Al starts high enough that six competing silicate engines
          // (feldspar, albite, quartz, tourmaline, beryl, spodumene) can all
          // draw on it for the full scenario AND leave residual for topaz
          // to nucleate in phase 3. 150 ppm is on the upper end of realistic
          // pegmatite pocket fluid Al but within published ranges
          // (London 2008, pegmatite fluid chemistry).
          "Al": 150,
          // Alkali feldspar chemistry — microcline first, then ev_albitization
          // flips K -> Na.
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 40,
          // Incompatible elements — these are the point of the scenario.
          // All start above their respective minimum thresholds but below
          // the nucleation σ threshold; they build (unused early) and then
          // the cascade fires.
          "Be": 25,    // beryl nucleation σ 1.8 — waits longest
          "B": 35,     // tourmaline σ 1.3 — fires earliest once hot
          "Li": 35,    // spodumene σ 1.5, also feeds elbaite
          "F": 25,     // topaz σ 1.4 — fires late when T drops into window
          // Color-element traces. Cr from hinted ultramafic contact;
          // Mn for morganite/kunzite/rubellite; Cu for the Paraíba long-shot.
          "Cr": 2.5,
          "Cu": 0.3,
          "V": 2.0,
          "Ti": 0.8,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "P": 8,    // accessory apatite [Cassedanne 1991]
          "Mg": 5,   // brief-required non-zero baseline
          "O2": 0.1,
          "pH": 6.8,
          "salinity": 6.0
        },
        // Pegmatite country rock — silicate, not acid-reactive on sim
        // timescales, so when pocket fluid turns mildly acidic in phase 3
        // pH stays low (no carbonate buffering). That's what lets
        // grow_feldspar's kaolinization branch fire on the microcline.
        "wall": {
          "composition": "pegmatite",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 8
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 5,   "type": "gem_pegmatite_outer_shell",        "name": "Outer Shell",        "description": "Wall-zone microcline + quartz" },
        { "step": 30,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_first_schorl",       "name": "Schorl Arrives",     "description": "B + Fe2+ supersaturation — first tourmaline" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_albitization",       "name": "Albitization",       "description": "K-feldspar -> albite replacement cascade" },
        { "step": 90,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_be_saturation",      "name": "Be Saturation",      "description": "Beryl finally nucleates — enormous crystals incoming" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "gem_pegmatite_li_phase",           "name": "Li Phase",           "description": "Spodumene + elbaite territory" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "gem_pegmatite_late_hydrothermal",  "name": "Late Hydrothermal",  "description": "Topaz window opens — F survivors fire" },
        { "step": 190, "type": "gem_pegmatite_clay_softening",     "name": "Clay Softening",     "description": "Kaolinite replaces pocket walls" },
        { "step": 215, "type": "gem_pegmatite_final",              "name": "Final Cooling",      "description": "System approaches 300C floor" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Morteani et al. 2002 — fluid chemistry of Brazilian gem pegmatites",
        "Cassedanne 1991 — Cruzeiro mine paragenesis",
        "Proctor 1985 — Cruzeiro tourmaline + beryl mineralogy",
        "London 2008 — pegmatite fluid Al partition (~150 ppm upper bound)"
      ]
    },

    "ouro_preto": {
      "anchor": "Ouro Preto Imperial Topaz veins, Minas Gerais, Brazil (Variant B per Morteani et al. 2002).",
      "description": "Hydrothermal topaz vein in Precambrian phyllite + quartzite. Single clean cooling curve from 360°C to 50°C — the 'anti-flash-quench' of the gem-pegmatite scenarios. F-pulse gates topaz nucleation; Cr leach commits the imperial color.",
      "expects_species": ["topaz", "quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 260,
      "notes": [
        "Hydrothermal veins cutting Precambrian phyllite and quartzite in the Ouro Preto district. Fluid inclusion data (Morteani et al. 2002) puts crystallization at ~360°C, 3.5 kbar from metamorphic brines derived from devolatilization of phyllite.",
        "Single clean cooling curve — 360°C → 50°C — the anti-flash-quench of the gem-pegmatite scenarios. No thermal events, no pressure spikes. One exhalation from the granite cooling below.",
        "The gate: topaz can't nucleate until fluorine accumulates past a saturation threshold. Early quartz grows alone. A mid-scenario metamorphic dehydration event (step 35) pumps F from the phyllite micas into the fluid, and the vein transitions to imperial topaz territory. The imperial color — golden-orange to pink — depends on Cr3+ dissolved out of nearby ultramafic bodies; without chromium the topaz is colorless or pale blue.",
        "Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026): Na=60, K=40 (phyllite muscovite/albite breakdown per Morteani 2002). Mg=15 (phyllite chlorite/biotite, brief-required non-zero baseline; conservative since host is quartzite + phyllite, not mafic)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 360.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Quartz-saturated metamorphic brine from devolatilizing phyllite.
          // SiO2 1200 ppm is enough to supersaturate quartz at 360C
          // (silica_equilibrium at 360C ~1050 ppm) — quartz lines the vein
          // walls first, as per real Ouro Preto paragenesis.
          "SiO2": 1200,
          "Ca": 40,
          "CO3": 20,
          "Fe": 6,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Al": 15,
          // Starts below F-threshold (20 ppm) — topaz waits for the pulse.
          "F": 12,
          // Trace Cr from nearby ultramafic contact. Starts sub-threshold;
          // ev_cr_leach bumps it into the imperial-color window (3-8 ppm).
          // Random seeds can push it past 8 (pink imperial) if the Cr leach
          // lands on an already-elevated baseline.
          "Cr": 0.5,
          "Ti": 0.6,
          // Audit gap-fills:
          "Na": 60,
          "K": 40,
          "Mg": 15,
          "O2": 0.3,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 3.0
        },
        // Ouro Preto topaz vein — 2 primary + 4 secondary bubbles;
        // hydrothermal vein in quartzite reads as a small cohesive pocket.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 9
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 5,   "type": "ouro_preto_vein_opening",      "name": "Vein Opening",       "description": "Fracture propagates, fresh brine" },
        { "step": 35,  "type": "ouro_preto_f_pulse",           "name": "F-Pulse",            "description": "Phyllite dehydration — F crosses saturation" },
        { "step": 55,  "type": "ouro_preto_cr_leach",          "name": "Cr Leach",           "description": "Ultramafic dike contributes chromium" },
        { "step": 90,  "type": "ouro_preto_steady_cooling",    "name": "Steady Cooling",     "description": "Main topaz growth phase" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "ouro_preto_late_hydrothermal", "name": "Late Hydrothermal",  "description": "Kaolinite softening, F depleted" },
        { "step": 200, "type": "ouro_preto_oxidation_stain",   "name": "Oxidation Stain",    "description": "Goethite staining, surface water" },
        { "step": 240, "type": "ouro_preto_final_cooling",     "name": "Final Cooling",      "description": "System approaches ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Morteani et al. 2002 — fluid inclusion microthermometry of Ouro Preto Imperial Topaz veins"
      ]
    },

    "deccan_zeolite": {
      "anchor": "Deccan Traps zeolite vesicle (Stage III, ~21-58 Ma post-eruption). Nashik 'bloody apophyllite' is the type expression. Per Ottens et al. 2019.",
      "description": "Patient zeolite-stage paragenesis in cooled basalt vesicles. Stage I silica veneer + Stage II zeolite blades + Stage III alkaline K-Ca-Si-F pulse builds pseudo-cubic apophyllite around hematite-needle phantoms.",
      // magnetite stopped firing under sim_version 20 (Phase C v1).
      // Same drift cause as bornite/porphyry — see that note. Restore
      // when chemistry tunes for the new sim version.
      "expects_species": ["hematite", "quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Per Ottens et al. 2019, the Deccan basalt vesicles fill in stages over tens of millions of years. Stage I (early): silica veneers, chalcedony coating. Stage II: zeolite blades (stilbite, scolecite, heulandite) and early calcite. Stage III: the apophyllite stage — alkaline K-Ca-Si-F fluid percolates through cooled basalt vesicles and crystallizes pseudo-cubic apophyllite blocks, sometimes carrying hematite-needle phantoms (the 'bloody apophyllite' of Nashik).",
        "Compared to the metamorphic / hydrothermal scenarios, this is gentle: no acid pulses, no dramatic T excursions. The story is patient crystallization in alkaline groundwater over geologic time.",
        "Audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): Sr=2 — Deccan zeolites (heulandite, stilbite, mesolite) carry Sr substituting for Ca, sometimes 100s of ppm in the mineral. Sim-scale 2 ppm in the parent fluid documents the source. Brief-required non-zero Mg already covered by Mg=8."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 250.0,    // hot Stage I post-eruption
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,     // vesicle in basalt — atmospheric-ish
        "fluid": {
          // Alkaline silica-rich groundwater leaching the basalt:
          // high SiO2 from glass + plagioclase weathering, low K and F
          // initially — those climb in Stage III when alkali-rich
          // groundwater finally percolates through, gating apophyllite
          // behind that explicit pulse so it doesn't preempt hematite.
          // Iron is already abundant from basalt groundmass leaching;
          // combined with high O2 it lets Stage I deposit hematite
          // needles before Stage III brings apophyllite.
          "SiO2": 900,
          "Ca": 180,
          "CO3": 80,
          "Fe": 180,
          "Mn": 4,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Al": 15,
          "K": 2,
          "Na": 40,
          "F": 1,
          // Audit gap-fill: zeolites carry Sr substituting for Ca.
          "Sr": 2,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 8.2,
          "salinity": 2.0
        },
        // Vesicle in basalt — single primary cavity with minor
        // post-eruption coalescence. Smooth, sub-spherical.
        "wall": {
          "composition": "basalt",
          "thickness_mm": 200.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 8000.0,    // iron-rich basalt host
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 400.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 21          // Deccan eruption ~66 Ma
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_silica_veneer",         "name": "Silica Veneer",          "description": "Stage I early chalcedony coating" },
        { "step": 35,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_hematite_pulse",        "name": "Hematite Pulse",         "description": "Iron seeds the vesicle wall — pre-zeolite needle deposition" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_stage_ii",              "name": "Zeolite Stage II",       "description": "Stilbite + heulandite + calcite blades" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "deccan_zeolite_apophyllite_stage_iii", "name": "Apophyllite Stage III", "description": "Alkaline K-Ca-Si-F pulse — apophyllite grows around the hematite needles, producing the 'bloody apophyllite' phantom band" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "deccan_zeolite_late_cooling",          "name": "Late Cooling",           "description": "System cools toward ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Ottens et al. 2019 — Deccan zeolite paragenesis + Stage III timing (21-58 Ma)",
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — Nashik 'bloody apophyllite' phantom inclusions"
      ]
    },

    "radioactive_pegmatite": {
      "anchor": "(generic high-T alkali-granite pocket — not anchored to a specific locality)",
      "description": "High-T pegmatitic fluid + U + Pb. Grows uraninite, smoky quartz (darkened by radiation), feldspar/albite, and late-stage galena from radiogenic Pb.",
      "expects_species": ["uraninite", "autunite", "quartz", "feldspar"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Generic testing scenario — not anchored to a real locality (per the user's clarification on the audit brief). Pegmatitic fluids are silica-saturated melts with abundant K + Na + Al + U.",
        "Mechanic: 4-event lifecycle. Crystallization pulse (step 20): main quartz + uraninite growth. Deep time (step 50): radiation slowly transmutes U → Pb, darkens nearby quartz. Oxidizing meteoric water (step 80): late-stage fracture flow brings O2; sulfides destabilize but uraninite endures. Final cooling (step 100): system approaches ambient, galena precipitates from the radiogenic Pb.",
        "Audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): Mg=5 — brief-required non-zero Mg baseline. Pegmatite pocket fluids are Mg-poor (Mg partitions into outer-shell biotite/chlorite during pegmatite differentiation), matches the gem_pegmatite scenario's Mg=5 abstraction."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=600C, P=2.0 kbar: pegmatite pocket conditions before
        // residual-fluid differentiation pulse drops it to 450C.
        "temperature_C": 600.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 2.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatitic fluids are silica-saturated melts — SiO2 must
          // be well above equilibrium (eq at 600C ~6000 ppm in our
          // model). Real pegmatites have extreme silica activity.
          "SiO2": 12000,
          "Ca": 50,
          "CO3": 20,
          "Fe": 60,
          "Mn": 8,
          "S": 40,
          "F": 25,
          "U": 150,   // primary uraninite source
          "Pb": 30,   // radiogenic Pb seed; grows over event timeline
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 50,
          "Al": 30,
          // Classic pegmatite-defining trace indicators — no current
          // mineral consumes them, but the narrator reads them as
          // beryl/spodumene/tourmaline/apatite country.
          "Be": 20,
          "Li": 40,
          "B": 25,
          "P": 8,
          // Audit gap-fill: brief-required non-zero Mg (pegmatite-pocket low value).
          "Mg": 5,
          "O2": 0.0,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        // Pegmatite pocket — fracture-controlled cavity, n=2 "slot" profile
        // (4 primaries + 5 secondaries).
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 6
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_crystallization", "name": "Pegmatite Crystallization", "description": "Main crystallization pulse" },
        { "step": 50,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_deep_time",       "name": "Deep Time",                  "description": "Eons pass — radiation accumulates" },
        { "step": 80,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_oxidizing",       "name": "Oxidizing Fluids",           "description": "Late-stage meteoric water" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_final_cooling",   "name": "Final Cooling",              "description": "System approaches ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "(generic testing scenario — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "schneeberg": {
      "anchor": "Schneeberg, Erzgebirgskreis (Saxony Ore Mountains), Germany — type locality for torbernite (1772), zeunerite (1872), uranospinite (1873), and ten more uranyl arsenate-phosphate species. Walpurgis Flacher vein, Weisser Hirsch Mine.",
      "description": "Schneeberg / Erzgebirge oxidized uranium-pegmatite vein system (Walpurgis Flacher vein, Weisser Hirsch Mine, Saxony — type locality for torbernite, zeunerite, and uranospinite). A U-bearing pegmatite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primary assemblage weathers under meteoric oxidation; the resulting uranyl + Cu + As fluid plates the autunite-group secondaries in two cation phases — Cu-rich first (torbernite emerald greens then zeunerite as As-pulse arrives), then Ca-dominant after Cu is consumed (autunite + uranospinite, the bright LW-UV fluorescent yellows).",
      "expects_species": ["uraninite", "torbernite", "zeunerite", "autunite", "uranospinite"],
      "duration_steps": 160,
      "notes": [
        "The mineralogically richest single ore district in Europe — the Erzgebirge had been mined for silver since the 1100s, then bismuth from the 1500s (the very name 'Bismutum' was coined here), then uranium from the 1800s onward. Most autunite-group species were first described from Schneeberg or its sister deposits (Jáchymov, Annaberg). Pinch & Wilson 1977 monographs are the canonical reference.",
        "Mechanic: 6-event lifecycle walking through cation×anion combinatorics. Pegmatite crystallization (step 20): hot reducing fluid grows uraninite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primaries. Cooling (step 70): T drops to ambient. Cu+P phase (step 85): O2 floods, primaries weather, P>As, Cu>Ca → torbernite plates. Cu+As pulse (step 105): As replenishes from arsenopyrite weathering, Cu still high → zeunerite plates. Cu depletion (step 125): Cu consumed by both Cu-cation secondaries; Ca rises from carbonate dissolution → autunite plates. As pulse late (step 145): As replenishes again, Ca dominant → uranospinite plates.",
        "First scenario to fire all 4 P/As-branch uranyl species (torbernite, autunite, zeunerite, uranospinite) in a single run. The cation+anion fork mechanic introduced by Rounds 9b-9e is finally exercised end-to-end. Uraninite weathers as the v12 gatekeeper feedstock event."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=450°C, P=1.5 kbar: pegmatitic residual fluid before
        // crystallization pulse drops it to ambient.
        "temperature_C": 450.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatite-saturated silica melt
          "SiO2": 8000,
          // Moderate Ca — will become dominant cation after Cu depletes.
          // Carbonate buffer ~20 from limestone country rock contact.
          "Ca": 50,
          "CO3": 20,
          "F": 20,
          // U=100: enough for primary uraninite at high T, plus broth
          // recharge during weathering. The v12 gatekeeper releases
          // ~7 ppm U per uraninite dissolution step (60% of 12% × ~100 µm).
          "U": 100,
          // Cu=80, Fe=40, S=30: chalcopyrite-saturating composition.
          // Cu also feeds torbernite + zeunerite during the supergene phase.
          "Cu": 80,
          "Fe": 40,
          "S": 30,
          // As=15: enough for arsenopyrite primary + post-weathering As
          // pulse for zeunerite/uranospinite. Bumped further by events.
          "As": 15,
          // P=12: phosphate for torbernite/autunite. Replenishment events
          // swing the P/As ratio across the run.
          "P": 12,
          // K=30: alkali pegmatite background; not enough to fire carnotite
          // (no V), and the cation gate filters by K/(K+Ca) anyway.
          "K": 30,
          // Pegmatite-defining traces — narrator reads these as Erzgebirge
          // country (beryl, spodumene, tourmaline, native bismuth).
          "Pb": 5,
          "Al": 25,
          "Mn": 5,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Be": 10,
          "Li": 15,
          "B": 12,
          // Bismuth — Schneeberg was named for its bismuth mining before
          // the uranium era. Bismuthinite + native_bismuth secondary phases
          // can form alongside the uranyls.
          "Bi": 10,
          // Strongly reducing initial — required for uraninite + sulfides.
          "O2": 0.0,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 6.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 9
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "schneeberg_pegmatite_crystallization", "name": "Pegmatite Crystallization", "description": "Reducing pegmatitic fluid grows uraninite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primaries" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "schneeberg_cooling",                   "name": "Cooling",                    "description": "T drops to ambient supergene window; primaries finish forming" },
        { "step": 85,  "type": "schneeberg_cu_p_phase",                "name": "Cu+P Oxidation",             "description": "Meteoric water floods; primaries weather; P>As, Cu>Ca → torbernite plates" },
        { "step": 105, "type": "schneeberg_cu_as_pulse",               "name": "Cu+As Pulse",                "description": "Arsenopyrite-derived As replenishes; As>P, Cu still dominant → zeunerite plates" },
        { "step": 125, "type": "schneeberg_cu_depletion",              "name": "Cu Depletion",               "description": "Cu consumed by torbernite+zeunerite; Ca rises (carbonate dissolution) → autunite plates" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "schneeberg_as_pulse_late",             "name": "Late As Pulse",              "description": "Final arsenate replenishment; Ca dominant → uranospinite plates, the bright fluorescent yellow finishes the assemblage" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — canonical Schneeberg/Erzgebirge monograph",
        "Weisbach 1872 — zeunerite type description (Walpurgis Flacher vein)",
        "Weisbach 1873 — uranospinite type description (Weisser Hirsch Mine)",
        "Klaproth 1789 — uranium discovery in Schneeberg pitchblende",
        "research/research-uranospinite.md (May 2026) — cation-fork mechanic + paragenesis"
      ]
    },

    "colorado_plateau": {
      "anchor": "Uravan Mineral Belt, Colorado Plateau — sandstone-hosted roll-front uranium-vanadium deposits (Triassic-Jurassic Morrison Formation). Includes the Carnotite-Eldorado, Uravan, and Moab districts; the V+U bonanza that drove the early-twentieth-century uranium industry decades before the Manhattan Project.",
      "description": "Uravan Mineral Belt sandstone roll-front uranium-vanadium deposit (Roc Creek, Montrose County, CO — carnotite type locality, Friedel & Cumenge 1899). Oxidizing groundwater carries U + V + K + Ca through Triassic-Jurassic Morrison Formation sandstones until it meets a reducing barrier (petrified wood, carbonaceous shale), where the metals drop out as bright canary-yellow uranyl-vanadate crusts. Carnotite + tyuyamunite are the two diagnostic species — interconvertible by cation exchange, drawn apart by whichever of K/Ca dominates the local pore fluid.",
      "expects_species": ["carnotite", "tyuyamunite"],
      "duration_steps": 180,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Colorado Plateau uranium districts (Uravan Mineral Belt). Mineralogy first described by Friedel & Cumenge (1899) at Roc Creek (Montrose County, CO); Hess (1924) characterized the V-U-Ca-K paragenesis. The Vanadium Corporation of America (VCA) operated the Uravan mill from 1915-1944 turning carnotite into V₂O₅ (steel alloy) before the Manhattan Project shifted demand to uranium.",
        "Mechanic: 5-event sandstone roll-front lifecycle. Initial: oxidizing surface groundwater carries U+V+K+Ca at ambient T. Step 20 (groundwater pulse): more U + V flushes through the system, Ca dominates K initially → tyuyamunite plates. Step 60 (roll-front contact): Fe rises (organic-iron proxy for petrified wood / carbonaceous shale), T drops, slight reducing pulse — concentrates carnotite + tyuyamunite at the redox front. Step 100 (cation oscillation): K rises (evaporite-style salt concentration in the arid surface zone), K/(K+Ca) crosses 0.5 → carnotite plates. Step 140 (Ca recovery): Ca returns dominant → second tyuyamunite phase. Step 165 (arid stabilization): system stabilizes, both species coexist.",
        "First scenario to fire carnotite + tyuyamunite, completing the autunite-group cation+anion fork coverage when paired with Schneeberg (which fires the Cu/Ca pair on the P+As branches)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=22°C, P=0.05 kbar: ambient near-surface roll-front conditions.
        "temperature_C": 22.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          // Sandstone matrix — moderate silica
          "SiO2": 200,
          // Ca dominant by background (groundwater Ca-bicarbonate)
          "Ca": 100,
          "CO3": 60,
          // U=15: realistic Colorado Plateau roll-front loading — enough
          // to cross the U>=0.3 secondary gates with margin. Bumped during
          // groundwater pulse event.
          "U": 15,
          // V=12: vanadium from earlier weathering of montroseite/roscoelite
          // (the primary V minerals; not yet in sim). Sufficient for carnotite
          // + tyuyamunite at supergene T.
          "V": 12,
          // K=20 baseline; gets bumped to dominant during step 100 oscillation.
          "K": 20,
          // Fe=8: trace iron, will rise during roll-front contact event.
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mg": 15,
          "Mn": 2,
          "S": 5,
          "Cl": 8,
          // No primary Cu/Pb/As — the scenario is U-V-K-Ca specifically.
          "Cu": 0,
          "Pb": 0,
          "As": 0,
          "P": 1,    // trace; not enough for autunite/torbernite
          // Initial mildly oxidizing — surface groundwater with O2 picked
          // up at the recharge boundary.
          "O2": 1.2,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        // Sandstone-hosted vug — high secondary porosity from intergranular
        // dissolution. n=4 'open' profile.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 8,
          "shape_seed": 5
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "colorado_plateau_groundwater_pulse",  "name": "Groundwater Pulse",      "description": "U+V replenishment from upstream sandstone weathering; Ca dominant → tyuyamunite begins plating" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "colorado_plateau_roll_front_contact", "name": "Roll-Front Contact",     "description": "Fe rises (organic-iron proxy); T drops; redox front concentrates uranyl-vanadates" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "colorado_plateau_k_pulse",            "name": "K Pulse",                "description": "Evaporite-style K enrichment; K/(K+Ca) crosses 0.5 → carnotite takes the cation pool" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "colorado_plateau_ca_recovery",        "name": "Ca Recovery",            "description": "Carbonate dissolution refreshes Ca; second tyuyamunite phase plates alongside carnotite" },
        { "step": 165, "type": "colorado_plateau_arid_stabilization", "name": "Arid Stabilization",     "description": "System reaches ambient steady state; both species coexist as in real Uravan specimens" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Friedel & Cumenge 1899 — original carnotite description (Roc Creek)",
        "Nenadkevich 1912 — tyuyamunite type description (Tyuya-Muyun)",
        "Hess 1924 — V-U-Ca-K paragenesis review",
        "Stern et al. 1956 — meta-tyuyamunite (American Mineralogist v.41)",
        "research/research-tyuyamunite.md (May 2026) — Colorado Plateau roll-front geology + simulator design"
      ]
    },

    // ============================================================
    // Tutorial scenarios (May 2026)
    // ============================================================
    // Surfaced in the New Game Menu under "Tutorials" — the recommended
    // first stop for new players. Structurally identical to scenarios
    // (scripted broth + scripted events) but scoped/paced for teaching.
    // The callout-overlay UI layer is a follow-up; in this slice they
    // run as plain scenarios you can drive manually in Creative Mode.
    // See proposals/TUTORIAL-SYSTEM-BUILDER-REVIEW.md for design context.
    // ============================================================

    "tutorial_first_crystal": {
      "anchor": "(tutorial scaffold — generic silica-rich broth)",
      "description": "Tutorial 1: First Crystal. Grow a quartz, then watch what happens when conditions drift out of its growth window.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 30,
      "notes": [
        "Tutorial scenario. Designed for the guided first-time-player experience: simple silica-rich broth, quartz nucleates within a few steps at 180°C, then a scripted temperature drop at step 8 pulls T well out of quartz's growth window. The intended player learning is: (1) clicking Advance moves time, (2) crystals need conditions in the right range, (3) when the conditions drift, growth stops.",
        "Surfaced in the New Game Menu under Tutorials. Not anchored to a real locality — it's a teaching scaffold. Sandbox-testable as a normal scenario without the callout overlay UI that ships in a follow-up.",
        "Broth shape mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.silica (the existing 'Silica-rich' starter fluid) so the lesson generalizes to that picker entry."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=180°C: quartz growth window center. Gives σ(Qz) ~1.2-1.5 at
        // start so quartz nucleates within a few steps. Drops to ~100°C
        // after the tutorial event, putting growth firmly outside the
        // comfort window without going so cold the crystal disappears.
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Silica-rich broth, mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.silica.
          "SiO2": 600,
          "Ca": 150,
          "CO3": 100,
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mn": 3,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Ti": 0.8,
          "Al": 4,
          "F": 10,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 8, "type": "tutorial_temperature_drop", "name": "Temperature Drops", "description": "Conditions drift out of quartz's growth window — the crystal stops growing" }
      ],
      // Tutorial overlay script consumed by the JS tutorial state machine
      // (window.startTutorial). Each step fires when fortressSim.step
      // reaches its `step` value. Authors should put one callout per
      // sim-step trigger (later steps replace earlier ones immediately).
      "tutorial": {
        "steps": [
          { "step": 0,  "anchor": "#f-advance",       "side": "top",   "text": "Welcome. This is your vug — an empty pocket inside rock, waiting for a crystal to grow. The broth around it is silica-rich and warm enough for quartz. Press 'Advance Step' to move time forward by ~50,000 years." },
          { "step": 4,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Quartz is forming on the wall. Each press of Advance grows it a little more. Notice the temperature sitting around 180°C — that's right in quartz's comfort window." },
          { "step": 9,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "The temperature just dropped sharply. Watch what happens to growth as you keep pressing Advance — the broth got colder, and cold silica wants to stay in solution rather than crystallize out." },
          { "step": 16, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Notice the log: 'no growth this step' is starting to appear. Your crystal is still there, beautiful, but no new layers are forming. The broth doesn't want to give up its silica anymore." },
          { "step": 25, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "That's the lesson: conditions control whether a crystal grows. Same broth, same crystal, different temperature — different outcome. Everything else in the game is just elaborations on this idea. (Press Home when ready, or keep going.)" }
        ]
      },
      "sources": [
        "(tutorial scaffold — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "tutorial_mn_calcite": {
      "anchor": "(tutorial scaffold — generic carbonate broth)",
      "description": "Tutorial 2: A Mn-Doped Calcite. Grow a calcite, then mix in manganese and watch the next zones glow orange-red under UV. Iron quenches; the boundary records the broth-history.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 30,
      "notes": [
        "Tutorial scenario. Teaches how additives change a growing crystal's properties: Mn²⁺ activates orange fluorescence in calcite (threshold 2 ppm) and Fe²⁺ quenches it. The carbonate broth ships with Fe:10 already at the quencher range and Mn:8 just past the activator threshold — early calcite zones incorporate Mn but stay dim under UV. The Mn pulse at step 8 pushes Mn well past the activator threshold; the Fe drop at step 16 clears the quencher. The boundary between dim early zones and bright late zones records the moment the broth changed.",
        "Surfaced in the New Game Menu under Tutorials. Not anchored to a real locality — it's a teaching scaffold. The Franklin/Sterling Hill (NJ) Mn-activated calcite glow is the real-world reference for the lesson.",
        "Broth shape mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.carbonate so the lesson generalizes to that picker entry."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=100°C: comfortable calcite growth window with retrograde
        // solubility helping nucleation. Stays warm enough through the
        // tutorial that calcite keeps growing (the lesson is about
        // properties, not growth interruption like Tutorial 1).
        "temperature_C": 100.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Carbonate broth, mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.carbonate.
          "SiO2": 80,
          "Ca": 300,
          "CO3": 250,
          "Fe": 10,
          "Mn": 8,
          "Mg": 12,
          "Ti": 0.2,
          "Al": 1,
          "F": 5,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 2
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 8,  "type": "tutorial_mn_pulse", "name": "Manganese Pulse",    "description": "Mn²⁺ injected — next calcite zones incorporate the activator" },
        { "step": 16, "type": "tutorial_fe_drop",  "name": "Iron-Poor Recharge", "description": "Fe²⁺ quencher cleared — Mn-doped zones fluoresce at full brightness" }
      ],
      // Tutorial overlay script — see tutorial_first_crystal for schema notes.
      "tutorial": {
        "steps": [
          { "step": 0,  "anchor": "#f-advance",       "side": "top",   "text": "This vug holds a carbonate broth — calcium and CO₃ ions floating around, waiting to crystallize. Calcite forms here. Press 'Advance Step' to begin." },
          { "step": 4,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Calcite is forming. The broth has a little manganese in it (Mn ≈ 8 ppm) — Mn²⁺ activates orange fluorescence in calcite under longwave UV. But the broth also has iron (Fe ≈ 10 ppm), and iron quenches that glow. So the early zones of your calcite are recording Mn but staying dim." },
          { "step": 9,  "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "A pulse just brought a lot more manganese into the broth. The next zones of calcite will incorporate Mn²⁺ heavily — but iron is still quenching most of the activation. Keep advancing." },
          { "step": 14, "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "The Mn is being recorded into every growth ring from here on. But you wouldn't see it glow yet — Fe is still suppressing the fluorescence. The broth is loaded with the right ingredient and the wrong inhibitor at the same time." },
          { "step": 17, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Iron just crashed out of the broth. The Mn-doped zones that grow next will fluoresce at full brightness. There's a boundary forming inside your crystal: dim early stripes from the iron-quenched phase, bright late stripes from now on." },
          { "step": 25, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "The crystal you grew is now a stratigraphic record of everything you put in the broth. Same crystal, written in fluorescence by every change in chemistry. This is what real Franklin / Sterling Hill calcite specimens look like under UV — bands of glow and quench, recording the deep-time fluid history of the vein." },
          { "step": 30, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "That's the lesson: additives change a growing crystal's properties. The vug remembers what you put into it. Tutorial complete. (Press Home when ready, or keep going.)" }
        ]
      },
      "sources": [
        "(tutorial scaffold — no published source)",
        "Franklin / Sterling Hill (NJ) — type locality for Mn-activated calcite fluorescence"
      ]
    }

  }
}
